-- Hong Kong shares rise on Wall St cues, hopes of more China support measures
-- By Chen Yixin and the Shanghai Newsroom
-- Thu Oct 09, 2014 04:10AM EDT
-- None



SHANGHAI, Oct 9 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares finished higher on Thursday, buoyed by gains in global markets on expectations that the Federal Reserve would keep interest rates low for a longer period.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> rose 1.2 percent to 23,534.53 points. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the top Chinese listings in Hong Kong climbed 0.9 percent. Investor sentiment also was underpinned by comments by Premier Li Keqiang published late on Wednesday that China would launch further major investment projects in information networks, water conservancy and environment protection this year. [ID:nL3N0S33AM] The leading percentage winner among H-shares was Shanghai Fosun Pharmaceutical Group <2196.HK>, which climbed 2.2 percent. The financial sector performed well, with Industrial and Commercial Bank of China <1398.HK> rising 0.6 percent, China Construction Bank <0939.HK> climbing 1.6 percent and HSBC Holdings PLC <0005.HK> gainning 0.8 percent.